{"title_page": "Myeongjong of Joseon", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = {{PAGENAME}}\n| title        = \n| titletext    = \n| more         = Kingdom of Great Joseon<br>\ub300\uc870\uc120\uad6d (\u5927\u671d\u9bae\u570b)<br>\uc870\uc120\uc655\uc870 (\u671d\u9bae\u738b\u671d)\n| type         = \n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| succession   = [[List of monarchs of Korea|King of Joseon]]\n| moretext     = \n| reign        = 1545\u20131567\n| reign-type   = \n| coronation   = \n| cor-type     = \n| predecessor  = [[Injong of Joseon]]\n| pre-type     = \n| regent       = [[Queen Munjeong]]<br />(1545\u20131565)\n| reg-type     = \n| successor    = [[Seonjo of Joseon]]\n| suc-type     = \n| spouse       = [[Queen Insun]]\n| spouse-type  = Consort\n| consort      = <!-- yes or no -->\n| issue        = Crown Prince Sunhoe\n| issue-link   = \n| issue-pipe   = \n| full name    = \n| era name     = \n| era dates    = \n| regnal name  = \n| posthumous name = King Myeongjong Gongheon Heoneui Somun Gwangsuk Gyeonghyo the Great of Korea<br>\uba85\uc885\uacf5\ud5cc\ud5cc\uc758\uc18c\ubb38\uad11\uc219\uacbd\ud6a8\ub300\uc655<br>\u660e\u5b97\u606d\u61b2\u737b\u6bc5\u662d\u6587\u5149\u8085\u656c\u5b5d\u5927\u738b\n| temple name  = '''Myeongjeong'''\n| house        = [[House of Yi|Jeonju Yi]]\n| house-type   = \n| father       = [[Jungjong of Joseon]]\n| mother       = [[Queen Munjeong]]\n| birth_date   = 3 July 1534\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = {{d-da|3 August 1567|3 July 1534}}\n| death_place  = \n| burial_date  = \n| burial_place = \n| occupation   = \n| signature_type = \n| signature    = \n| religion     = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name|\nhangul=\uba85\uc885|\nhanja=\u660e\u5b97|\nrr=Myeongjong|\nmr=My\u014fng-jong|\nhangulborn=\uc774\ud658|\nhanjaborn=\u674e\u5cd8|\nrrborn=I Hwan|\nmrborn=I Hwan\n}}\n{{Joseon Dynasty monarchs}}\n\n'''Myeongjong of Joseon''' (3 July 1534 &ndash; 3 August 1567, r. 1545&ndash;1567) was the 13th king of the [[Joseon Dynasty]] of [[Korea]]. He was the second son of [[Jungjong of Joseon|Jungjong]], and his mother was [[Queen Munjeong]], who was Jungjong's third queen.\n\nHe became king in 1545 at the age of 12 following the death of his half-brother, [[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]. Since he was too young to rule the kingdom, Queen Munjeong governed the nation in his name.\n\n==Biography==\n===Political factions===\nThere were two political factions at the time Myeongjong came to power; Greater Yun, headed by [[Yun Im]], [[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]'s maternal uncle,<ref>Yun Im is the older brother of Queen Janggyeong (Injong's mother).</ref> and Lesser Yun, headed by Myeongjong's maternal uncles, [[Yun Won-hyeong]] and Yun Wonro.<ref>They were Queen Munjeong's older brother.</ref> (Yun Im and Yun Brothers were close relatives by that period's standards - Yun Im's great-grandfather was older brother of Yun Brothers' great-great-grandfather.)  Greater Yun took power in 1544, when Injong succeeded Jungjong; but they failed to wipe out their opposition, since [[Queen Munjeong]] protected the Lesser Yun faction and other opposition officials.\n\nAfter the death of Injong in 1545, Lesser Yun replaced Greater Yun as the majority in the royal court and brutally ousted their adversaries in the [[Korean Literati Purges|Fourth Literati Purge of 1545]]. Yun Im was executed, as were many of his followers.\n\n===Rise of Yun Won-hyeong===\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\nThe Lesser Yun faction continued to attack their opposition. In 1546, Yun Won-hyeong impeached his older brother, Yun Won-ro, who was executed a few days later along with his followers. Facing no opposition from the government, Yun Won-hyeong became Minister of Personnel \uc774\uc870\ud310\uc11c in 1548, Left State Councilor in 1551 and ultimately [[Yeonguijeong|Chief State Councilor]] \uc601\uc758\uc815  in 1563.\n\nDespite Yun Won-hyeong's violent rule, [[Queen Munjeong]] was an effective administrator, distributing to the common people land formerly owned by the nobility. However, she held on to rule even after the king reached his majority at the age of 20.\n\n===Death of Queen Munjeong===\nAfter the death of Queen Munjeong in 1565, the king decided to rule the kingdom by himself and had his uncle Yun Won-hyeong put to death, along with his second wife<ref>Originally his concubine, [[Chung Nanjung]] had the first wife, Lady Kim, poisoned to death.</ref> Jeong Nan-jeong, who also rose to power due to her close friendship and being second sister-in-law to Queen Munjeong.<ref>She became a dictator; the real power behind the veil of Queen Munjeong's regency.</ref><ref>Actually, Jeong Nan-jeong committed suicide as a domino effect of misfortunes: Queen Munjeong's death, and her loss of control of the government.</ref> Yun Won-hyeong allowed corruption to flourish in the government; while the kingdom was unstable, [[Jurchens]], [[Japan]]ese, and rebellious troops rampaged at will and threatened the government itself. Rebel leader Im Kkeok-jeong was arrested and executed in 1552, but outside invasion continued; the Joseon Dynasty had to re-mobilize its army and navy along to protect its borders.\n\n===Death and succession===\nMyeongjong tried to reform the government after taking power into his own hands by recalling and reinstating [[Sarim scholars]] who were exiled in the purge, but died only two years later without any male issue.<ref>His only son, the Crown Prince, died 4 years before his own death.</ref> [[Seonjo of Joseon|King Seonjo]], his half-nephew, succeeded to the throne in 1567.\n\n==Family==\n* Father: [[Jungjong of Joseon|King Jungjong of Joseon]] (16 April 1488 \u2013 29 November 1544) (\uc870\uc120 \uc911\uc885)\n**Grandfather: [[Seongjong of Joseon|King Seongjong of Joseon]] (19 August 1457 \u2013 20 January 1494) (\uc870\uc120 \uc131\uc885)\n**Grandmother: [[Queen Jeonghyeon|Queen Jeonghyeon of the Papyeong Yun clan]] (21 July 1462 \u2013 13 September 1530) (\uc815\ud604\uc655\ud6c4 \uc724\uc528)\n* Mother: [[Queen Munjeong|Queen Munjeong of the Papyeong Yun clan]] (2 December 1501 \u2013 5 May 1565) (\ubb38\uc815\uc655\ud6c4 \uc724\uc528)\n**Grandfather: Yun Ji-Im (1475 \u2013 14 April 1534) (\uc724\uc9c0\uc784)\n**Grandmother: Lady Lee of the Jeonui Lee clan (1475 \u2013 1511) (\uc804\uc758 \uc774\uc528)\n* Consorts and their Respective Issue(s):\n#[[Queen Insun|Queen Insun of the Cheongsong Shim clan]] (27 June 1532 \u2013 12 February 1575) (\uc778\uc21c\uc655\ud6c4 \uc2ec\uc528)\n##[[Crown Prince Sunhoe|Yi Bu, Crown Prince Sunhoe]] (1 July 1551 \u2013 6 October 1563) (\uc774\ubd80 \uc21c\ud68c\uc138\uc790)  \n#Royal Noble Consort Gyeong of the Jeonui Lee clan (1541 \u2013 June 1595) (\uacbd\ube48 \uc774\uc528)\n#Royal Noble Consort Sun of the Jeong clan (? \u2013 1592) (\uc21c\ube48 \uc815\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Gwi-in of the Shin clan (\uadc0\uc778 \uc2e0\uc528)\n#Royal Consort So-ui of the Shin clan (1533 \u2013 1565) (\uc18c\uc758 \uc2e0\uc528) \n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Han clan (\uc219\uc758 \ud55c\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Jeong clan (\uc219\uc758 \uc815\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Jeong clan (\uc219\uc758 \uc815\uc528)\n\n==His full posthumous name==\n* King Myeongjong Gongheon Heoneui Somun Gwangsuk Gyeonghyo the Great of Korea\n* \uba85\uc885\uacf5\ud5cc\ud5cc\uc758\uc18c\ubb38\uad11\uc219\uacbd\ud6a8\ub300\uc655\n* \u660e\u5b97\u606d\u61b2\u737b\u6bc5\u662d\u6587\u5149\u8085\u656c\u5b5d\u5927\u738b\n\n==Popular culture==\n* Portrayed by Seo Dong-hyun in the 2013 [[KBS2]] TV series ''[[The Fugitive of Joseon]]''.\n* Portrayed by [[Lee David]] in the 2016 [[JTBC]] TV series ''[[Mirror of the Witch]]''.\n* Portrayed by [[Seo Ha-joon]] in the 2016 [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] TV series ''[[The Flower in Prison]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.koreandb.net/Koreanking/html/person/pki60013.htm\n* http://chosonsillok.org/inspection/insp_king.jsp?id=kma{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Yi]]||1534||1567}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of monarchs of Korea|King of Joseon]]|years=1545\u20131567\n|regent1=[[Queen Munjeong]]|years1=1545\u20131565}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seonjo of Joseon|Seonjo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Myeongjong Of Joseon}}\n[[Category:1534 births]]\n[[Category:1567 deaths]]\n[[Category:Joseon rulers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Korean monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = {{PAGENAME}}\n| title        = \n| titletext    = \n| more         = Kingdom of Great Joseon<br>\ub300\uc870\uc120\uad6d (\u5927\u671d\u9bae\u570b)<br>\uc870\uc120\uc655\uc870 (\u671d\u9bae\u738b\u671d)\n| type         = \n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| succession   = [[List of monarchs of Korea|King of Joseon]]\n| moretext     = \n| reign        = 1545\u20131567\n| reign-type   = \n| coronation   = \n| cor-type     = \n| predecessor  = [[Injong of Joseon]]\n| pre-type     = \n| regent       = [[Queen Munjeong]]<br />(1545\u20131565)\n| reg-type     = \n| successor    = [[Seonjo of Joseon]]\n| suc-type     = \n| spouse       = [[Queen Insun]]\n| spouse-type  = Consort\n| consort      = <!-- yes or no -->\n| issue        = Crown Prince Sunhoe\n| issue-link   = \n| issue-pipe   = \n| full name    = \n| era name     = \n| era dates    = \n| regnal name  = \n| posthumous name = King Myeongjong Gongheon Heoneui Somun Gwangsuk Gyeonghyo the Great of Korea<br>\uba85\uc885\uacf5\ud5cc\ud5cc\uc758\uc18c\ubb38\uad11\uc219\uacbd\ud6a8\ub300\uc655<br>\u660e\u5b97\u606d\u61b2\u737b\u6bc5\u662d\u6587\u5149\u8085\u656c\u5b5d\u5927\u738b\n| temple name  = '''Myeongjeong'''\n| house        = [[House of Yi|Jeonju Yi]]\n| house-type   = \n| father       = [[Jungjong of Joseon]]\n| mother       = [[Queen Munjeong]]\n| birth_date   = 3 July 1534\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = {{d-da|3 August 1567|3 July 1534}}\n| death_place  = \n| burial_date  = \n| burial_place = \n| occupation   = \n| signature_type = \n| signature    = \n| religion     = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name|\nhangul=\uba85\uc885|\nhanja=\u660e\u5b97|\nrr=Myeongjong|\nmr=My\u014fng-jong|\nhangulborn=\uc774\ud658|\nhanjaborn=\u674e\u5cd8|\nrrborn=I Hwan|\nmrborn=I Hwan\n}}\n{{Joseon Dynasty monarchs}}\n\n'''Myeongjong of Joseon''' (3 July 1534 &ndash; 3 August 1567, r. 1545&ndash;1567) was the 13th king of the [[Joseon Dynasty]] of [[Korea]]. He was the second son of [[Jungjong of Joseon|Jungjong]], and his mother was [[Queen Munjeong]], who was Jungjong's third queen.\n\nHe became king in 1545 at the age of 12 following the death of his half-brother, [[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]. Since he was too young to rule the kingdom, Queen Munjeong governed the nation in his name.\n\n==Biography==\n===Political factions===\nThere were two political factions at the time Myeongjong came to power; Greater Yun, headed by [[Yun Im]], [[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]'s maternal uncle,<ref>Yun Im is the older brother of Queen Janggyeong (Injong's mother).</ref> and Lesser Yun, headed by Myeongjong's maternal uncles, [[Yun Won-hyeong]] and Yun Wonro.<ref>They were Queen Munjeong's older brother.</ref> (Yun Im and Yun Brothers were close relatives by that period's standards - Yun Im's great-grandfather was older brother of Yun Brothers' great-great-grandfather.)  Greater Yun took power in 1544, when Injong succeeded Jungjong; but they failed to wipe out their opposition, since [[Queen Munjeong]] protected the Lesser Yun faction and other opposition officials.\n\nAfter the death of Injong in 1545, Lesser Yun replaced Greater Yun as the majority in the royal court and brutally ousted their adversaries in the [[Korean Literati Purges|Fourth Literati Purge of 1545]]. Yun Im was executed, as were many of his followers.\n\n===Rise of Yun Won-hyeong===\n{{unrferenced section|date=April 2020}}\nThe Lesser Yun faction continued to attack their opposition. In 1546, Yun Won-hyeong impeached his older brother, Yun Won-ro, who was executed a few days later along with his followers. Facing no opposition from the government, Yun Won-hyeong became Minister of Personnel \uc774\uc870\ud310\uc11c in 1548, Left State Councilor in 1551 and ultimately [[Yeonguijeong|Chief State Councilor]] \uc601\uc758\uc815  in 1563.\n\nDespite Yun Won-hyeong's violent rule, [[Queen Munjeong]] was an effective administrator, distributing to the common people land formerly owned by the nobility. However, she held on to rule even after the king reached his majority at the age of 20.\n\n===Death of Queen Munjeong===\nAfter the death of Queen Munjeong in 1565, the king decided to rule the kingdom by himself and had his uncle Yun Won-hyeong put to death, along with his second wife<ref>Originally his concubine, [[Chung Nanjung]] had the first wife, Lady Kim, poisoned to death.</ref> Jeong Nan-jeong, who also rose to power due to her close friendship and being second sister-in-law to Queen Munjeong.<ref>She became a dictator; the real power behind the veil of Queen Munjeong's regency.</ref><ref>Actually, Jeong Nan-jeong committed suicide as a domino effect of misfortunes: Queen Munjeong's death, and her loss of control of the government.</ref> Yun Won-hyeong allowed corruption to flourish in the government; while the kingdom was unstable, [[Jurchens]], [[Japan]]ese, and rebellious troops rampaged at will and threatened the government itself. Rebel leader Im Kkeok-jeong was arrested and executed in 1552, but outside invasion continued; the Joseon Dynasty had to re-mobilize its army and navy along to protect its borders.\n\n===Death and succession===\nMyeongjong tried to reform the government after taking power into his own hands by recalling and reinstating [[Sarim scholars]] who were exiled in the purge, but died only two years later without any male issue.<ref>His only son, the Crown Prince, died 4 years before his own death.</ref> [[Seonjo of Joseon|King Seonjo]], his half-nephew, succeeded to the throne in 1567.\n\n==Family==\n* Father: [[Jungjong of Joseon|King Jungjong of Joseon]] (16 April 1488 \u2013 29 November 1544) (\uc870\uc120 \uc911\uc885)\n**Grandfather: [[Seongjong of Joseon|King Seongjong of Joseon]] (19 August 1457 \u2013 20 January 1494) (\uc870\uc120 \uc131\uc885)\n**Grandmother: [[Queen Jeonghyeon|Queen Jeonghyeon of the Papyeong Yun clan]] (21 July 1462 \u2013 13 September 1530) (\uc815\ud604\uc655\ud6c4 \uc724\uc528)\n* Mother: [[Queen Munjeong|Queen Munjeong of the Papyeong Yun clan]] (2 December 1501 \u2013 5 May 1565) (\ubb38\uc815\uc655\ud6c4 \uc724\uc528)\n**Grandfather: Yun Ji-Im (1475 \u2013 14 April 1534) (\uc724\uc9c0\uc784)\n**Grandmother: Lady Lee of the Jeonui Lee clan (1475 \u2013 1511) (\uc804\uc758 \uc774\uc528)\n* Consorts and their Respective Issue(s):\n#[[Queen Insun|Queen Insun of the Cheongsong Shim clan]] (27 June 1532 \u2013 12 February 1575) (\uc778\uc21c\uc655\ud6c4 \uc2ec\uc528)\n##[[Crown Prince Sunhoe|Yi Bu, Crown Prince Sunhoe]] (1 July 1551 \u2013 6 October 1563) (\uc774\ubd80 \uc21c\ud68c\uc138\uc790)  \n#Royal Noble Consort Gyeong of the Jeonui Lee clan (1541 \u2013 June 1595) (\uacbd\ube48 \uc774\uc528)\n#Royal Noble Consort Sun of the Jeong clan (? \u2013 1592) (\uc21c\ube48 \uc815\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Gwi-in of the Shin clan (\uadc0\uc778 \uc2e0\uc528)\n#Royal Consort So-ui of the Shin clan (1533 \u2013 1565) (\uc18c\uc758 \uc2e0\uc528) \n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Han clan (\uc219\uc758 \ud55c\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Jeong clan (\uc219\uc758 \uc815\uc528)\n#Royal Consort Suk-ui of the Jeong clan (\uc219\uc758 \uc815\uc528)\n\n==His full posthumous name==\n* King Myeongjong Gongheon Heoneui Somun Gwangsuk Gyeonghyo the Great of Korea\n* \uba85\uc885\uacf5\ud5cc\ud5cc\uc758\uc18c\ubb38\uad11\uc219\uacbd\ud6a8\ub300\uc655\n* \u660e\u5b97\u606d\u61b2\u737b\u6bc5\u662d\u6587\u5149\u8085\u656c\u5b5d\u5927\u738b\n\n==Popular culture==\n* Portrayed by Seo Dong-hyun in the 2013 [[KBS2]] TV series ''[[The Fugitive of Joseon]]''.\n* Portrayed by [[Lee David]] in the 2016 [[JTBC]] TV series ''[[Mirror of the Witch]]''.\n* Portrayed by [[Seo Ha-joon]] in the 2016 [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] TV series ''[[The Flower in Prison]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.koreandb.net/Koreanking/html/person/pki60013.htm\n* http://chosonsillok.org/inspection/insp_king.jsp?id=kma{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Yi]]||1534||1567}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Injong of Joseon|Injong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of monarchs of Korea|King of Joseon]]|years=1545\u20131567\n|regent1=[[Queen Munjeong]]|years1=1545\u20131565}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seonjo of Joseon|Seonjo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Myeongjong Of Joseon}}\n[[Category:1534 births]]\n[[Category:1567 deaths]]\n[[Category:Joseon rulers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Korean monarchs]]\n", "name_user": "XXX8906", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRise of Yun Won-hyeong", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myeongjong_of_Joseon"}
{"title_page": "35th Filmfare Awards", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film awards\n| number = 35\n| award = Filmfare Awards\n| image = \n| caption = \n| date = 1990\n| site = \n| host = \n| producer = \n| director = \n| best_film = ''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]''\n| best_critic = ''[[Khayal Gatha]]''\n| most_wins = ''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]'' (6)\n| most_nominations = ''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]'' (12)\n| network = \n| duration = \n| ratings = \n| last = 34th\n| next = 36th\n}}\n\nThe '''35th Filmfare Awards''' were held in 1990. [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s [[Maine Pyaar Kiya]] was named the Best Film of the year. [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]]'s [[Parinda]] was the other big winner on the night. This rivalry between [[Sooraj Barjatya]] and [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]] resurfaced in the [[40th Filmfare Awards]], where once again [[Sooraj Barjatya]]'s [[Hum Aapke Hain Kaun]] beat out [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]]'s [[1942 A Love Story]] for Best Film.\n\n==Main awards==\n[[File:Vidhu Vinod Chopra March 2015.jpg|alt=|thumb|197x197px|[[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]] \u2014 Best Director winner for [[Parinda]]]]\n[[File:JackieShroff.jpg|alt=|thumb|189x189px|[[Jackie Shroff]] \u2014 Best Actor winner for [[Parinda]]]]\n[[File:Sridevi.jpg|alt=|thumb|198x198px|[[Sridevi]] \u2014 Best Actress winner for [[ChaalBaaz]]]]\n[[File:Nana Patekar (Image 2), at IFFI Goa, 2017.jpg|alt=|thumb|149x149px|[[Nana Patekar]] \u2014 Best Supporting Actor winner for [[Parinda]]]]\n[[File:Rakhee Gulzar.jpg|alt=|thumb|149x149px|[[Raakhee]] \u2014 Best Supporting Actress winner for [[Ram Lakhan]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82; width:50%;\"|[[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82; width:50%;\"|[[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]'''''\n**''[[Chandni]]''\n**''[[Parinda]]''\n**''[[Ram Lakhan]]''\n**''[[Salaam Bombay]]''\n| valign=\"top\"|\n*'''''[[Vidh